en_172359_0	The national ceremony to mark the inauguration of the ‘Suraksha’ Insurance scheme introduced by the Ministry of Education was held under the patronage of President Maithripala Sirisena and Prime Minister Ranil Wickremesinghe at Temple Trees this morning (02).
en_172359_1	The beneficiaries of this scheme will include nearly 4.5 million students between 5 to 19 years of age.
en_172359_2	Students attending government schools, assisted private schools, non-assisted private schools, international schools and student monks are included in the scheme.
en_172359_3	Sources from the Ministry of Education have stated that registration for the insurance scheme is compulsory and all data files relating to them are now being processed.
en_172359_4	Students need not pay any premium for this insurance as all relevant payments are made by the government.
en_172359_5	The Government initially allocated 2,700 million rupees towards this scheme under the 2017 budget and the scheme is being handled by the Sri Lanka Insurance Corporation.
en_172359_6	The maximum annual cover for hospitalization and medical services for a child is Rs.
en_172359_7	200,000.
en_172359_8	Expenses up to Rs.100,000 at a time could be reimbursed for a child for a hospitalization.
en_172359_9	Medical examinations fees without hospitalization could also be reimbursed.
en_172359_10	When a child obtains treatment from a government hospital, payment of Rs.100 per day will be paid for a period of 30 days.
en_172359_11	When in-house treatment from a government hospital is obtained, a maximum of Rs.10,000 would be paid for diagnostic laboratory tests conducted outside.
en_172359_12	If treatment is obtained from any private hospital registered with the Health Ministry, a maximum payment of Rs.100,000 will be paid at a given time.
en_172359_13	Children receiving treatment under the ‘Suraksha’ scheme will be entitled to a 20 percent discount on hospital charges and medical consultant fees.
en_172359_14	This follows a discussion between the Education Minister and the Private Hospital Association and Consultant Medical Practitioners’ Association.
en_172359_15	The maximum room charges for a day paid at a private hospital, ward at a government hospital or a fee-levying Ayurveda Hospital is Rs.5000.
en_172359_16	Maximum room charges paid per annum will be Rs.60, 000.
en_172359_17	There is also a provision to obtain insurance cover for treatment and doctors charges, even without hospitalization, as there is an annual cover up to a maximum of Rs.10,000 for 7 types of illnesses.
en_172359_18	In the event of a child’s death due to an accident, Rs.100, 000 will be paid as compensation.
en_172359_19	In the event of a parents death Rs.75,000 with be allocated towards the child’s education.
en_172359_20	If a student suffers permanent disability, Rs.100, 000 will be paid as compensation while Rs.50,000 will be paid as compensation for partial disability.
en_172359_21	During his address, President Maithripala Sirisena stated that the government is dedicated to protecting the nation’s children.
